  "Option A costs more (total interest ~$39,300)": "",
  "Option A total interest = ~$39,300. Option B: 15% of $1,000,000 = $150,000 in equity value given up. Equity financing costs far more when the business grows significantly, though it carries less cash flow risk since there are no required monthly payments.": "",
  "A business has a $50,000 line of credit at 9% annual interest. In January, it draws $20,000 and repays $10,000 in February. How much interest does it owe for January (assume 30-day month)?": "",
  "$375": "",
  "$75": "",
  "$150": "",
  "$450": "",
  "Interest for January = $20,000 x 9% / 12 = $20,000 x 0.0075 = $150. Interest is only charged on the amount actually drawn, not the full credit limit.": "",
  "A small business factors $80,000 in invoices at a 15% discount to receive immediate cash. How much cash does the business receive, and what is the cost of factoring?": "",
  "Receives $64,000, cost is $16,000": "",
  "Receives $72,000, cost is $8,000": "",
